  "description": "The sample space is the set of all possible outcomes of a probabilistic experiment — everything that could happen, listed exhaustively. For a coin flip, the sample space is Ω={heads,tails}\\Omega = \\{\\text{heads}, \\text{tails}\\}. For rolling a standard die, Ω={1,2,3,4,5,6}\\Omega = \\{1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6\\}. For measuring the temperature outside right now, Ω\\Omega might be the real numbers, or more realistically some interval like [−50,60][-50, 60] degrees Celsius. The sample space is the universe within which probability operates: everything that receives a probability must be expressible in terms of outcomes from Ω\\Omega.\n",
